the day the film is finished.

1024
01:58:09,720 --> 01:58:12,314
I dream of filming
a romantic epic,

1025
01:58:12,480 --> 01:58:16,189
a tragic love story
like that of John Nicol.

1026
01:58:19,160 --> 01:58:20,798
Here is the story.

1027
01:58:22,120 --> 01:58:24,270
In July 1789,

1028
01:58:24,680 --> 01:58:27,433
a ship of the royal fleet
leaves the port of London

1029
01:58:27,600 --> 01:58:32,276
carrying 245 women
and bound for Australia.

1030
01:58:33,480 --> 01:58:36,120
Cook has just
discovered the continent

1031
01:58:36,320 --> 01:58:38,914
and the fleshly needs
of the settlers must be met

1032
01:58:39,320 --> 01:58:41,596
and the new colony populated.

1033
01:58:42,920 --> 01:58:45,389
Mainly thieves and prostitutes,

1034
01:58:45,720 --> 01:58:49,873
the government had taken them out of prison
to deport them to Australia.

1035
01:58:51,240 --> 01:58:54,756
Among them
is a young girl of 18,

1036
01:58:54,960 --> 01:58:57,031
Sarah Whitelam.

1037
01:58:58,640 --> 01:59:02,076
The crew, led by
His Majesty's officers,

1038
01:59:02,360 --> 01:59:04,636
counts all sorts of sailors

1039
01:59:04,840 --> 01:59:09,232
including a 34-year old Scotsman,
John Nicol.

1040
01:59:11,360 --> 01:59:14,990
They hug the coast of Africa
and cross the Indian Ocean

1041
01:59:15,240 --> 01:59:18,198
on a voyage
that will last 10 months.

1042
01:59:22,080 --> 01:59:26,199
John Nicol falls madly in love
with Sarah Whitelam,

1043
01:59:26,680 --> 01:59:30,469
and their love
grows stronger over the journey.

1044
01:59:31,640 --> 01:59:35,429
Sarah is one of the 50 women
to give birth

1045
01:59:35,640 --> 01:59:37,631
during the voyage.

1046
01:59:45,360 --> 01:59:49,149
On arriving in Australia,
John Nicol has to leave Sarah

1047
01:59:49,560 --> 01:59:53,633
and return to England,
according to the terms of his contract.

1048
01:59:54,760 --> 01:59:59,197
He swears he will return
as soon as he can, and sails away.

1049
02:00:02,640 --> 02:00:05,393
Years pass before he returns.

1050
02:00:05,640 --> 02:00:09,793
But when he does, Sarah
is no longer there.

1051
02:00:10,440 --> 02:00:12,113
He makes enquiries

1052
02:00:12,320 --> 02:00:15,915
and discovers she has left
on a ship heading for Bombay.

1053
02:00:16,840 --> 02:00:20,151
What no one dares tell him,
and what he would never find out,

1054
02:00:20,520 --> 02:00:24,309
is that she is married
to a settler,

1055
02:00:24,480 --> 02:00:25,879
mother of two children.

1056
02:00:29,480 --> 02:00:33,110
John Nicol leaves for Bombay
and searches everywhere for her.

1057
02:00:33,800 --> 02:00:37,430
He searches in the countryside,
he searches in the city,

1058
02:00:37,640 --> 02:00:39,836
but finds her nowhere.

1059
02:00:40,720 --> 02:00:43,633
He looks for her all over,
but finds nothing.

1060
02:00:45,560 --> 02:00:49,918
So he leaves and travels
to all the ports in the world.

1061
02:00:50,640 --> 02:00:53,678
Cape Town, Buenos Aires,

1062
02:00:54,280 --> 02:00:57,318
London, Rio de Janeiro,

1063
02:00:57,880 --> 02:01:01,236
Santa Cruz, Batavia,

1064
02:01:01,720 --> 02:01:04,234
Zanzibar, Bombay,

1065
02:01:04,520 --> 02:01:06,909
Sidney, Canton,

1066
02:01:07,240 --> 02:01:09,800
Macau, Tangier,

1067
02:01:10,280 --> 02:01:12,635
Lisbon, Recife,

1068
02:01:12,920 --> 02:01:15,878
Salvador de Bahia, Havana,

1069
02:01:16,200 --> 02:01:19,352
Valparaiso, Bilbao
and Port-Louis,

1070
02:01:19,640 --> 02:01:21,995
La Rochelle and Porto Ribeira...

1071
02:01:22,520 --> 02:01:26,229
For over 25 years,
John Nicol travelled the world

1072
02:01:26,480 --> 02:01:28,630
going all the way round, twice.

1073
02:01:29,120 --> 02:01:32,750
He landed on six continents,
fought with pirates

1074
02:01:32,960 --> 02:01:34,758
and Napoleon's fleet,

1075
02:01:34,960 --> 02:01:39,352
made friends in China,
Jamaica and Hawaii.

1076
02:01:39,880 --> 02:01:43,236
But he never found Sarah Whitelam.

1077
02:01:53,080 --> 02:01:57,631
At the beginning of the 19th century,
exhausted, he returned home,

1078
02:01:57,840 --> 02:01:59,478
to Scotland.

1079
02:02:06,040 --> 02:02:10,398
He wrote: "By then I was too old
to look for her further,

1080
02:02:10,760 --> 02:02:13,673
and I didn't know
where in the world she was,

1081
02:02:13,920 --> 02:02:17,231
or even if she was still alive."

1082
02:02:19,600 --> 02:02:21,352
For in 1822,

1083
02:02:21,520 --> 02:02:24,751
a publisher in Edinburgh
asked to publish his memoirs.

1084
02:02:26,920 --> 02:02:30,595
Having no money to live on,
John Nicol accepted.

1085
02:02:30,920 --> 02:02:34,550
But he was old now,
and had forgotten the dates

1086
02:02:34,720 --> 02:02:36,631
and places of his journeys.

1087
02:02:38,280 --> 02:02:40,191
All he now remembered

1088
02:02:40,400 --> 02:02:43,074
was the name of the woman
he had loved all his life,

1089
02:02:44,200 --> 02:02:46,350
Sarah Whitelam.

1090
02:03:32,680 --> 02:03:34,591
Victor Hugo used to come here.

1091
02:03:37,040 --> 02:03:39,759
It's one of the places
where he liked to write.

1092
02:03:43,760 --> 02:03:46,434
But when you go back
over the writer's path,

1093
02:03:46,680 --> 02:03:50,275
it becomes clear that the dates
and places of his manuscripts

1094
02:03:50,560 --> 02:03:53,393
do not always correspond
to reality.

1095
02:03:55,560 --> 02:03:58,120
Many of his texts
served him as an alibi

1096
02:03:58,400 --> 02:03:59,993
to be elsewhere,

1097
02:04:00,200 --> 02:04:03,670
a place where he met
his love dreams.

1098
02:04:06,160 --> 02:04:10,757
One of these loves,
the strongest, was Juliette Drouet.

1099
02:04:12,560 --> 02:04:14,676
A young orphan,
fresh from the convent,

1100
02:04:14,880 --> 02:04:18,271
and turned actress.
She met Victor Hugo

1101
02:04:18,480 --> 02:04:20,073
and they became lovers.

1102
02:04:20,720 --> 02:04:22,757
She left everything for him,

1103
02:04:23,120 --> 02:04:26,272
following him like a shadow
for 50 years.

1104
02:04:27,920 --> 02:04:32,756
Over the years, she wrote him
over 20,000 love letters.

1105
02:05:44,480 --> 02:05:46,994
There are so many images,
everywhere.

1106
02:05:47,760 --> 02:05:51,435
So many images of the other,
the elsewhere,

1107
02:05:51,840 --> 02:05:55,196
that you think:
"Why go out anymore,

1108
02:05:55,680 --> 02:05:58,638
out there, into the landscapes,

1109
02:05:58,880 --> 02:06:01,872
the horizons we've already seen,
already shown?"

1110
02:06:04,240 --> 02:06:07,392
Might as well stay home,
with oneself

1111
02:06:07,560 --> 02:06:10,234
and imagine the other,
the elsewhere,

1112
02:06:10,680 --> 02:06:13,069
and tell stories.

1113
02:06:14,240 --> 02:06:16,390
For though there are
too many images,

1114
02:06:17,240 --> 02:06:19,470
points of view are lacking,

1115
02:06:19,680 --> 02:06:22,274
and there are still
stories to be told.

1116
02:07:04,720 --> 02:07:09,078
I'd like to film the story,
or rather the journey, of Lobera,

1117
02:07:09,800 --> 02:07:13,077
a Spanish aristocrat
from the 13th century.

1118
02:07:15,920 --> 02:07:20,630
He vowed to go to Jerusalem
with the fourth crusade.

1119
02:07:21,600 --> 02:07:24,433
But, after much thought,

1120
02:07:24,800 --> 02:07:28,270
the length of the journey
and his fear of the Saracens

1121
02:07:28,560 --> 02:07:30,437
made him change his mind.

1122
02:07:31,760 --> 02:07:34,070
He then undertook,
on his estate,

1123
02:07:34,360 --> 02:07:36,874
a long imaginary journey.

1124
02:07:37,280 --> 02:07:40,671
For over a year,
he toured his estate

1125
02:07:41,160 --> 02:07:44,437
four times a day
until he had covered

1126
02:07:44,640 --> 02:07:49,111
the same distance as that
between his castle and Jerusalem.

1127
02:08:53,280 --> 02:08:54,475
In the 18th century,

1128
02:08:54,680 --> 02:08:57,991
Bougainville also leaves
on a trip around the world.

1129
02:08:59,080 --> 02:09:03,313
A certain Commerson is chosen
as naturalist for the expedition

1130
02:09:03,720 --> 02:09:07,111
and boards ship with his
young domestic, Jean Baret,

1131
02:09:07,440 --> 02:09:11,559
who is in fact his servant
and mistress, Jeanne Baret.

1132
02:09:12,360 --> 02:09:16,035
Women are not allowed on board
His Majesty's ships

1133
02:09:16,480 --> 02:09:18,437
and Jeanne is disguised as a man.

1134
02:09:19,920 --> 02:09:24,153
She manages to fool the crew
for over a year.

1135
02:09:26,320 --> 02:09:28,834
They reach the coasts of Brazil,

1136
02:09:29,360 --> 02:09:33,752
hug the coast of South America
and enter the Pacific Ocean.

1137
02:09:36,720 --> 02:09:41,271
They arrive in Polynesia and
Bougainville is in seventh heaven.

1138
02:09:43,880 --> 02:09:47,430
But as they disembark,
the naked natives

1139
02:09:47,640 --> 02:09:51,315
<i>rush towards Jeanne Bare!
Shouting: “ A woman, a woman!“</i>

1140
02:09:51,480 --> 02:09:53,630
and start to undress her.

1141
02:09:56,960 --> 02:10:00,157
Unmasked,
Bougainville questions her

1142
02:10:00,440 --> 02:10:02,829
and she lies to protect her lover,

1143
02:10:03,040 --> 02:10:05,919
saying that Commerson
is aware of nothing.

1144
02:10:08,560 --> 02:10:11,120
Generously, Bougainville

1145
02:10:11,280 --> 02:10:13,999
drops them off on Mauritius
on the home journey

1146
02:10:14,240 --> 02:10:16,390
to avoid them being punished.

1147
02:10:17,720 --> 02:10:19,358
Commerson lived another 5 years,

1148
02:10:19,480 --> 02:10:22,393
before falling ill and dying,

1149
02:10:22,600 --> 02:10:26,195
but not before he named a flower
after his young mistress:

1150
02:10:26,480 --> 02:10:28,471
the Baretia.

1151
02:10:30,440 --> 02:10:33,876
Later, Jeanne married
a French soldier

1152
02:10:34,200 --> 02:10:38,910
and returned to Europe with him,
thus ending her trip around the world.

1153
02:10:46,480 --> 02:10:50,155
Of Jeanne Baret, the first woman
to sail around the world,

1154
02:10:50,440 --> 02:10:52,716
there is not a single image.

1155
02:10:53,800 --> 02:10:56,997
Unless it be
the image of a flower.

1156
02:11:11,080 --> 02:11:14,710
Today, the immensity of space
leads to other journeys,

1157
02:11:14,960 --> 02:11:16,473
ever further.

1158
02:11:17,440 --> 02:11:21,354
And we look at the universe
like the frogs watch the cabin,

1159
02:11:21,680 --> 02:11:24,115
with the same curiosity.

1160
02:11:27,440 --> 02:11:29,078
And we send out signals.

1161
02:11:30,640 --> 02:11:32,517
The space probe Voyager

1162
02:11:32,800 --> 02:11:35,758
has long since left our galaxy.

1163
02:11:36,200 --> 02:11:40,353
It will outlast the solar system
and all life on earth.

1164
02:11:41,400 --> 02:11:45,871
It carries sounds, voices,
music from our planet.

1165
02:12:34,040 --> 02:12:37,476
Worlds appear and disappear...

1166
02:12:39,640 --> 02:12:42,792
This is the last moment
of the Ubykh language.

1167
02:12:46,680 --> 02:12:50,833
This man from Anatolia is dead
and with him died the Ubykh language,

1168
02:12:51,080 --> 02:12:52,912
which he was the last to speak.

1169
02:12:56,240 --> 02:13:01,155
The last sounds of this strange language
were a set of lies.

1170
02:13:01,760 --> 02:13:06,277
"For," he said, "There are no words
without lies."

1171
02:13:25,080 --> 02:13:28,038
The police have just arrested
a cinema student

1172
02:13:28,200 --> 02:13:30,919
who was prostituting herself
to pay for her studies.

1173
02:13:31,960 --> 02:13:34,918
Under the streetlamp,
she was reading Kant.

1174
02:13:37,040 --> 02:13:39,998
She told them
the parable of the pigeon.

1175
02:13:42,280 --> 02:13:47,116
"When the pigeon flies, it struggles
against the resistance of the air,

1176
02:13:47,320 --> 02:13:50,790
and imagines it would be easier
to fly in empty space.

1177
02:13:51,200 --> 02:13:54,192
But if it flew in empty space,
it would fall.

1178
02:13:58,520 --> 02:14:02,195
In order not to fall,
one must learn to resist,"

1179
02:14:02,480 --> 02:14:04,357
she told them.

1180
02:14:40,040 --> 02:14:43,670
It would be the tale of
a young filmmaker, just starting out.

1181
02:14:46,560 --> 02:14:50,519
He wants to film rebellion,
resistance,

1182
02:14:50,760 --> 02:14:52,990
rejection of the world
the way it is.

1183
02:14:55,120 --> 02:14:57,873
First, he writes a script

1184
02:14:58,120 --> 02:15:00,191
and gets together a big team.

1185
02:15:01,040 --> 02:15:03,634
There's music
and professional actors.

1186
02:15:04,440 --> 02:15:06,272
Ready? Action!

1187
02:15:08,800 --> 02:15:12,430
It could be the tale
of this young woman, in England,

1188
02:15:12,560 --> 02:15:14,278
in the fifties.

1189
02:15:15,360 --> 02:15:16,919
Maybe she's a spy.

1190
02:15:19,520 --> 02:15:23,639
She could be a Russian spy,
supporting the revolutionary cause.

1191
02:15:25,920 --> 02:15:29,709
Or an Indian terrorist, fighting
for her country's independence.

1192
02:15:48,680 --> 02:15:52,469
But something's wrong,
it's all too heavy.

1193
02:15:53,600 --> 02:15:57,912
So he writes a simpler fiction
and films it near home.

1194
02:16:00,760 --> 02:16:02,433
The actress is the same,

1195
02:16:02,880 --> 02:16:05,918
now a Maoist militant
in the sixties,

1196
02:16:07,440 --> 02:16:10,671
but the mother and father
are not professional actors.

1197
02:16:17,080 --> 02:16:20,072
Careful, silence,

1198
02:16:21,240 --> 02:16:22,833
we're filming.

1199
02:16:24,880 --> 02:16:26,075
But something's wrong,

1200
02:16:28,200 --> 02:16:31,238
because reality doesn't follow
his script.

1201
02:16:40,160 --> 02:16:41,639
So, he stops writing

1202
02:16:42,160 --> 02:16:45,710
and plunges his actress into
the social fringe of the eighties.

1203
02:16:47,240 --> 02:16:50,039
OK for the sound.

1204
02:17:00,800 --> 02:17:03,110
But something is still wrong,

1205
02:17:03,840 --> 02:17:06,434
is not synchronous with reality.

1206
02:17:11,680 --> 02:17:13,876
So he drops the whole team

1207
02:17:14,840 --> 02:17:19,152
and makes portraits of the rebels,
the marginals of his time.

1208
02:17:49,440 --> 02:17:52,558
But he still feels
that something is wrong.

1209
02:17:52,800 --> 02:17:55,189
He feels the gap
between them and him,

1210
02:17:55,520 --> 02:17:58,160
and realizes it's just an image.

1211
02:18:00,400 --> 02:18:02,357
So, he sets off alone

1212
02:18:02,600 --> 02:18:06,912
realizing he must stop expressing
his rebellion through others' eyes.

1213
02:18:12,040 --> 02:18:14,395
He starts to film the world:

1214
02:18:15,200 --> 02:18:16,315
water,

1215
02:18:16,680 --> 02:18:18,398
stones,

1216
02:18:18,720 --> 02:18:20,711
clouds.

1217
02:18:24,440 --> 02:18:28,195
Yes, that's how it could end:

1218
02:18:28,840 --> 02:18:31,992
he films the clouds,
over and over...

1219
02:18:34,680 --> 02:18:39,436
Then he understands
that he simply has to watch them,

1220
02:18:41,440 --> 02:18:44,796
that he must stop
wanting to reproduce the world...

1221
02:21:11,040 --> 02:21:14,192
Is this OK?
- Yes, that's fine.

1222
02:21:16,480 --> 02:21:18,710
Look at me.

1223
02:22:12,800 --> 02:22:14,791
I'd like to film all the places

1224
02:22:15,080 --> 02:22:18,630
all the things in the world
called "I don't know'

1225
02:22:19,280 --> 02:22:21,476
or "I don't understand"

1226
02:22:21,720 --> 02:22:24,155
because of the surprising encounters

1227
02:22:24,360 --> 02:22:26,749
between travellers and natives.

1228
02:22:28,240 --> 02:22:31,676
When Captain Cook
arrived in Australia,

1229
02:22:31,920 --> 02:22:35,675
he pointed to an animal
and asked what it was called.

1230
02:22:36,240 --> 02:22:40,473
The aborigine answered:
"I don't understand":

1231
02:22:41,240 --> 02:22:43,231
kangourou.

1232
02:22:44,040 --> 02:22:49,114
Cook actually died due to
a misunderstanding in Hawaii.

1233
02:22:49,520 --> 02:22:52,273
The natives, thinking he was a god,

1234
02:22:52,480 --> 02:22:55,359
ate him and
were awaiting his return.

1235
02:22:56,920 --> 02:23:01,073
When Cook's companions
explained that he was human,

1236
02:23:01,280 --> 02:23:04,636
that he was now dead
and would not return,

1237
02:23:05,240 --> 02:23:07,117
the natives apologized

1238
02:23:07,400 --> 02:23:11,030
and gave back the bits
they had not eaten.

1239
02:23:19,880 --> 02:23:24,829
My story box
is a reservoir of dream films.

1240
02:23:25,160 --> 02:23:28,437
An Italian woman
in a hospital in Lugo, Italy,

1241
02:23:28,600 --> 02:23:32,036
who fell into
a deep coma six months ago,

1242
02:23:32,200 --> 02:23:34,874
a few weeks
after falling pregnant,

1243
02:23:35,120 --> 02:23:38,033
shed a tear on Thursday
as she gave birth to her baby.

1244
02:23:38,200 --> 02:23:42,114
All these amazing stories
come from everyday life.

1245
02:23:42,760 --> 02:23:45,229
Like the one
of the old Polish lady

1246
02:23:45,440 --> 02:23:47,590
whose portrait I'd like to do.

1247
02:23:49,600 --> 02:23:51,557
She's 113 years old.

1248
02:23:52,680 --> 02:23:57,072
When asked what it was like
to be so old

1249
02:23:57,480 --> 02:24:01,155
she said she was afraid
she might never die.

1250
02:24:17,440 --> 02:24:20,910
So I raise my glass
to those who are dead, the ancestors,

1251
02:24:21,160 --> 02:24:25,119
to you, Jean Rouch, who I often saw
make this gesture of offering,

1252
02:24:25,320 --> 02:24:27,391
a salute to the ancestors.

1253
02:24:34,560 --> 02:24:37,313
To you, who watched
the dancing Dogon masks

1254
02:24:37,480 --> 02:24:39,596
that you brought over to Paris,

1255
02:24:40,960 --> 02:24:43,793
the masks from
the cliffs of Bandiagara

1256
02:24:44,120 --> 02:24:47,112
that Germaine Dieterlen
had taught you about.

1257
02:25:59,600 --> 02:26:04,071
Hail to the ancestors, to those
who are drunk with adventure,

1258
02:26:04,440 --> 02:26:07,592
to those for whom drunkenness
represents the disorder

1259
02:26:07,760 --> 02:26:09,751
at the origin of the world,

1260
02:26:09,960 --> 02:26:14,272
for the souls of the dead are thirsty,
as you used to say, Jean.

1261
02:26:23,840 --> 02:26:27,231
Rouch, who filmed the Dogons
for years,

1262
02:26:27,480 --> 02:26:31,075
often spoke to me of the
Bandiagara cliffs where they live.

1263
02:26:32,240 --> 02:26:35,437
He spoke of it as
a mythical, magical place,

1264
02:26:35,680 --> 02:26:38,752
an apparition
in a Chirico landscape.

1265
02:26:40,320 --> 02:26:43,153
But since Rouch,
so many others have been there,

1266
02:26:43,480 --> 02:26:46,518
so many other images
of these cliffs have been made,

1267
02:26:46,840 --> 02:26:49,150
that I wanted to dream my own.

1268
02:29:09,600 --> 02:29:11,193
There was...

1269
02:29:11,920 --> 02:29:13,831
There was a dream...

1270
02:29:15,080 --> 02:29:17,879
There was the dream
of a film with Jan.

1271
02:29:19,520 --> 02:29:22,478
Jan was a mechanic
and a musician.

1272
02:29:25,280 --> 02:29:27,999
I remember filming him
one evening.

1273
02:29:28,640 --> 02:29:31,837
My name is Jan
and I like mechanics.

1274
02:29:38,840 --> 02:29:41,434
Could you move closer to the light?
- Yes.

1275
02:29:41,600 --> 02:29:45,036
Could you move your face
closer to the light. OK.

1276
02:29:49,880 --> 02:29:53,475
The film never got made
because Jan left for Africa,

1277
02:29:53,680 --> 02:29:55,000
to do aid work.

1278
02:29:57,280 --> 02:30:00,113
Months later, I received
a letter from him,

1279
02:30:00,560 --> 02:30:03,598
on December 6th,
a letter from Africa,

1280
02:30:04,480 --> 02:30:06,756
on Saint Nicolas Day.

1281
02:30:09,320 --> 02:30:13,439
I read Jan's words
and watched what I had just filmed.

1282
02:30:14,040 --> 02:30:15,838
I got lost between
here and there,

1283
02:30:17,120 --> 02:30:20,192
between my images
and what I was reading.

1284
02:30:22,480 --> 02:30:27,475
Jan wrote about their inability
to contain a starving crowd.

1285
02:30:28,320 --> 02:30:31,551
He described the disorder,
the pushing,

1286
02:30:31,720 --> 02:30:36,157
the crush to grab some food,
to survive.

1287
02:30:39,120 --> 02:30:41,873
Then he said that he
and the others on the mission

1288
02:30:42,120 --> 02:30:45,192
went back to their camp,
shocked at what they had seen.

1289
02:30:45,960 --> 02:30:50,511
Then he, like the others,
broke down and cried.

1290
02:30:53,720 --> 02:30:57,554
He wrote: "A

 the men
break down and cry.

1291
02:30:58,080 --> 02:31:01,311
But the women hold up."

1292
02:31:02,240 --> 02:31:06,791
He told me how fascinated he was
by their resistance.

1293
02:31:37,520 --> 02:31:40,672
Between the beginning and the end
of the Mahabharata,

1294
02:31:41,080 --> 02:31:43,117
right in the middle of the tale,

1295
02:31:43,400 --> 02:31:45,391
there is a pond,

1296
02:31:45,720 --> 02:31:47,677
a magic pond,

1297
02:31:48,600 --> 02:31:52,195
and if Yudhishtira
wants to pass,

1298
02:31:52,480 --> 02:31:54,994
he must answer these questions:

1299
02:31:58,640 --> 02:32:01,154
What is swifter than the wind?

1300
02:32:03,480 --> 02:32:04,754
Thought.

1301
02:32:06,480 --> 02:32:08,835
Give me an example of sorrow.

1302
02:32:10,960 --> 02:32:12,519
Ignorance.

1303
02:32:13,240 --> 02:32:15,595
An example of defeat.

1304
02:32:17,280 --> 02:32:18,998
Victory.

1305
02:32:20,440 --> 02:32:23,193
Which is the most cunning animal?

1306
02:32:25,040 --> 02:32:28,431
The one man has not yet
managed to know.

1307
02:32:29,480 --> 02:32:31,756
What causes the world?

1308
02:32:32,960 --> 02:32:34,473
Love.

1309
02:32:35,160 --> 02:32:37,117
What is your opposite?

1310
02:32:38,640 --> 02:32:40,199
Myself.

1311
02:32:40,840 --> 02:32:45,311
What about rebellion?
Why do men rebel?

1312
02:32:48,080 --> 02:32:52,756
To find beauty,
in life, or in death.

1313
02:32:54,480 --> 02:32:58,155
What is inevitable for all of us?

1314
02:33:01,040 --> 02:33:02,997
Happiness.

1315
02:33:04,040 --> 02:33:06,395
Happiness is inevitable.

1316
02:33:07,800 --> 02:33:12,237
Now tell me,
what is the greatest marvel?

1317
02:33:13,880 --> 02:33:15,996
The greatest marvel

1318
02:33:16,520 --> 02:33:19,160
is that each day, death strikes
all around us

1319
02:33:19,480 --> 02:33:22,233
yet we live as if we were immortal.

1320
02:33:22,960 --> 02:33:25,554
That is the greatest marvel.

1321
02:34:45,200 --> 02:34:48,670
There's a film to be made
about Bernard Moitessier.

1322
02:34:51,440 --> 02:34:55,399
In 1968,
the Golden Globe was organized,

1323
02:34:55,520 --> 02:34:59,991
the first round-the-world race,
solo and without stopovers.

1324
02:35:01,480 --> 02:35:04,552
Moitessier was one of nine
to take up the challenge.

1325
02:35:05,600 --> 02:35:09,230
He left on his yacht
with no help,

1326
02:35:09,480 --> 02:35:13,519
no radio equipment,
taking only a little tape recorder.

1327
02:35:19,520 --> 02:35:22,797
After ten months of sailing,
he was in the lead

1328
02:35:23,120 --> 02:35:26,590
and was preparing to sail up
the Atlantic towards England

1329
02:35:26,800 --> 02:35:30,111
where the Golden Globe
awaited him,

1330
02:35:30,480 --> 02:35:33,518
along with a reward
of 5000 sterling pounds

1331
02:35:33,760 --> 02:35:36,718
and, naturally, fame.

1332
02:35:37,200 --> 02:35:39,396
He would be the first sailor ever

1333
02:35:39,640 --> 02:35:43,395
to sail single-handed
around the world

1334
02:35:43,680 --> 02:35:45,637
without stopovers.

1335
02:35:47,560 --> 02:35:49,039
But, on April 18th,

1336
02:35:49,240 --> 02:35:53,757
he catapulted a message
onto the deck of a passing ship:

1337
02:35:54,520 --> 02:35:57,558
"I am sailing on
to the Pacific Islands,

1338
02:35:57,800 --> 02:35:59,598
because I am happy at sea,

1339
02:35:59,840 --> 02:36:02,878
and perhaps also,
to save my soul."

1340
02:36:04,320 --> 02:36:08,473
Turning his back on glory,
he sailed on to Polynesia.

1341
02:36:09,320 --> 02:36:10,879
I am truly happy at sea.

1342
02:36:11,120 --> 02:36:14,590
You can't imagine how good
I feel, alone, peaceful.

1343
02:36:15,800 --> 02:36:19,794
It's not always easy,
but when things go well, it's...

1344
02:36:21,240 --> 02:36:24,073
It's fantastic,
all the things I have felt.

1345
02:36:24,480 --> 02:36:26,790
It's something that...

1346
02:36:26,960 --> 02:36:31,716
So I don't want to stop now.
It would be stupid to return to Europe.

1347
02:36:31,920 --> 02:36:34,275
I was always on the go there.

1348
02:36:34,480 --> 02:36:37,393
I could never live a whole month

1349
02:36:37,520 --> 02:36:40,717
- what I call living -
really living...

1350
02:36:40,960 --> 02:36:42,712
Letting the sun inside you,

1351
02:36:42,920 --> 02:36:46,197
finding a deep sense of peace.

1352
02:36:46,360 --> 02:36:49,716
I never found that in France,
I never did,

1353
02:36:50,400 --> 02:36:51,799
not for a whole month.

1354
02:36:51,960 --> 02:36:55,078
There were small joys,
snatched from time to time.

1355
02:36:57,640 --> 02:37:00,234
I cannot go back to France,

1356
02:37:00,800 --> 02:37:02,757
truly, I cannot."

1357
02:37:08,240 --> 02:37:12,473
Moitessier is the man who could
have equalled Achilles' glory,

1358
02:37:12,720 --> 02:37:17,078
but rejected it to become
Ulysses, the traveller.

1359
02:37:19,840 --> 02:37:22,593
By his death before
the ramparts of Troy

1360
02:37:22,800 --> 02:37:26,839
Achilles answered the question:
"Why die?"

1361
02:37:29,360 --> 02:37:32,432
But Ulysses,
who sailed the seas,

1362
02:37:32,680 --> 02:37:36,560
then returned to his family,
only to leave again,

1363
02:37:37,400 --> 02:37:41,553
was seeking the answer
to the question:

1364
02:37:42,320 --> 02:37:44,357
"How to live?"

1365
02:38:32,720 --> 02:38:34,757
There's a film I dream of making

1366
02:38:35,040 --> 02:38:38,874
but which I never will, because
I'll no longer be of this world.

1367
02:38:40,920 --> 02:38:43,514
One day, after 2060,

1368
02:38:43,880 --> 02:38:46,440
the world population
will stop growing

1369
02:38:46,600 --> 02:38:49,069
and start to decrease.

1370
02:38:50,360 --> 02:38:52,510
I would like to film
the headlines

1371
02:38:52,720 --> 02:38:56,395
announcing this unique news
in the history of humanity.

1372
02:38:56,880 --> 02:38:59,349
And I would like to film
the slow disruption

1373
02:38:59,800 --> 02:39:03,111
it would cause to man's relationship
with the world,

1374
02:39:03,880 --> 02:39:05,314
with animals,

1375
02:39:06,040 --> 02:39:07,474
with himself.

1376
02:39:40,280 --> 02:39:41,679
It's winter.

1377
02:39:43,240 --> 02:39:45,311
The dog is sleeping.

1378
02:39:47,120 --> 02:39:51,432
Far from everything and everyone,
the film hibernates.

1379
02:39:52,680 --> 02:39:54,273
I listen to the radio

1380
02:39:56,520 --> 02:39:58,318
and I travel...

1381
02:43:43,080 --> 02:43:44,991
A moment of the world...

1382
02:43:46,160 --> 02:43:49,039
To sit alone at a terrace

1383
02:43:49,240 --> 02:43:51,436
and watch the world.

1384
02:44:12,960 --> 02:44:16,032
For years,
when I saw a pile of ashes,

1385
02:44:16,360 --> 02:44:19,557
I imagined lovers,
awaiting their beloved,

1386
02:44:19,880 --> 02:44:24,431
hour after hour, smoking
one cigarette after another.

1387
02:44:30,160 --> 02:44:32,720
Then one day, sitting at a terrace,

1388
02:44:32,920 --> 02:44:36,470
I saw a car draw up
and a door open...

1389
02:44:45,360 --> 02:44:46,759
A moment of the world.

1390
02:44:47,160 --> 02:44:50,835
Yes, I'd like to film
a moment of the world.

1391
02:44:54,320 --> 02:44:56,596
I'd watch the young women pass,

1392
02:44:57,200 --> 02:45:00,670
and think of Baudelaire's poem,
To a Passerby.

1393
02:45:01,760 --> 02:45:05,310
Baudelaire is sitting there,
at the terrace of a cafe,

1394
02:45:06,120 --> 02:45:08,714
he is alone, drinking.

1395
02:45:10,480 --> 02:45:12,676
Suddenly a woman passes

1396
02:45:12,960 --> 02:45:16,237
and glances at him
for a brief moment.

1397
02:45:16,560 --> 02:45:19,791
In that instant, he knows
he'll never see her again,

1398
02:45:20,400 --> 02:45:24,359
that he knows nothing about her,
that she is disappearing into the void.

1399
02:45:25,680 --> 02:45:28,069
And his poem, addressed to her,

1400
02:45:28,600 --> 02:45:33,071
ends with these words:
"Oh you, whom I would have loved,

1401
02:45:33,680 --> 02:45:36,115
Oh you, who knew it."

1402
02:45:58,080 --> 02:46:01,277
I dream of filming the gaze
of the women who pass.

1403
02:46:03,080 --> 02:46:06,038
And I dream
of filming friendly faces.

1404
02:46:08,280 --> 02:46:11,352
And I dream of filming
the vastness of the cosmos

1405
02:46:11,480 --> 02:46:15,235
where, perhaps,
all the souls of the universe meet.

1406
02:46:18,120 --> 02:46:20,680
I dream of filming
the face of an old lady

1407
02:46:20,880 --> 02:46:23,759
and finding there
the infancy of the world.

1408
02:46:27,040 --> 02:46:30,271
And I dream of filming
the desire of children.

1409
02:46:33,280 --> 02:46:36,398
And I dream of filming
the desire of lovers.

1410
02:46:39,840 --> 02:46:42,753
And I dream of filming desire...

1411
02:47:16,520 --> 02:47:18,670
I dream that it's summer,

1412
02:47:19,480 --> 02:47:23,713
that I offer Jean-Marie
a small role in a dream film.

1413
02:47:26,160 --> 02:47:30,358
It would be the film of a man
who, all his life, had done but one thing:

1414
02:47:31,480 --> 02:47:33,357
portraits of his dog.

1415
02:48:14,240 --> 02:48:16,117
But some dream films

1416
02:48:16,440 --> 02:48:19,114
are impossible to make.

1417
02:48:23,520 --> 02:48:28,754
For years, the same photo appeared
in the obituaries of a daily paper.

1418
02:48:30,320 --> 02:48:35,474
Every 27th of September,
the photo of lmgard and the words:

1419
02:48:35,640 --> 02:48:40,635
1982 - 1989 Already <i>7</i> years
Always close to you, Uncle.

1420
02:48:42,960 --> 02:48:45,793
But some films
must be kept silent,

1421
02:48:47,360 --> 02:48:49,920
some films will never be made,

1422
02:48:52,440 --> 02:48:55,114
some films are impossible to make.

1423
02:49:00,920 --> 02:49:02,558
Jean-Marie fell,

1424
02:49:02,960 --> 02:49:05,076
then entered a coma...

1425
02:49:10,280 --> 02:49:13,636
His heart, as big as a house,

1426
02:49:14,080 --> 02:49:16,356
beat on for a long while.

1427
02:49:19,520 --> 02:49:21,431
Then he left.

1428
02:50:13,520 --> 02:50:15,431
Jean-Marie's story,

1429
02:50:16,200 --> 02:50:18,111
like Ulysses' story,

1430
02:50:18,400 --> 02:50:20,118
like all stories,

1431
02:50:20,480 --> 02:50:21,834
tells us:

1432
02:50:22,680 --> 02:50:24,830
we cannot live without dreams,

1433
02:50:25,400 --> 02:50:26,720
without lies,

1434
02:50:27,200 --> 02:50:29,237
without illusions.

1435
02:52:09,680 --> 02:52:15,358
A film by Eric Pauwels

1436
02:54:38,440 --> 02:54:41,671
Subtitling: Tongues Untied
